After a long, wet winter moss can develop on driveways, patios and pathways. Moss can be removed using chemicals but this can have an impact on the surrounding environment. Instead, homeowners can resort to more natural methods such as soda crystals. In a video for Dri Pak, homeowners have been shown how to remove moss using soda crystals. The video has been captioned: “A simple way to remove moss from drives and patios with soda crystals.” Homeowners will need a 1.5kg bag of soda crystals or more depending on the size of the space. Firstly, homeowners need to liberally sprinkle the soda crystals on the area. READ MORE: How to prune hydrangeas: Common mistake when cutting hydrangeas It’s best not to do this on a windy day. Homeowners need to dampen the area if it is windy or the ground is particularly dry. This can be done with a hose or watering can. The soda crystals need to be left to soak into the moss for two or more days until it’s brown.  DON'T MISSHow to save spring bulbs after flowering - 4 easy steps to follow [INSIGHT]Mrs Hinch fans share dishwasher tablet tip to clean oven doors [UPDATE]Avoid keeping milk in door compartment of fridge to save hundreds [ANALYSIS] Once the moss is brown, the moss can be removed. Homeowners can do the with a stiff yard brush or a shovel. Once the moss is removed, the rest of the soda crystals can be washed away. Any remaining debris can be removed with the stiff brush. Looking for a new home, or just fancy a look? Add your postcode below or visit InYourArea The area will no longer be “slippery” with moss. Soda crystals can also help to remove mud, grime and mould. They can also be used to clean wooden decking which is also often prone to algae and moss. Using hot water and the soda crystals should help with this.  Soda crystals are available to buy in 1kg bags from most major supermarkets. Dri-Pak Soda Crystals are available to buy from Ocado for 80p. Wilko Original Soda Crystals are just £1.50.